<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from BiblioFox Research (HSR 033)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt">BiblioFox</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:14pt"> Research (HSR 033)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">1. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">BiblioFox</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> Research is a research consultancy established in 2000. We specialise in document-based research and archival research and have recently been </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">investigating the implications of the HS2 business case for existing intercity services on the West Coast, East Coast and Midland Main Lines.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">2. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">In our opinion </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">there is a fundamental contradiction at the heart of the HS2 strategic case.  This concerns pla</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> to divert </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">north-south </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">intercity travellers to HS2 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">services</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> and remove </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">a high number of </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">‘classic’ </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">i.e</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">traditional</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> intercity services from </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">existing </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">north-south </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">lines</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">thus </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">freeing those lines </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">for more commuter, regional and freight services.  We </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">exp</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">lain </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">this contradiction below.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">3. On the one hand, the Government says its aim is that “all towns and cities which currently have a direct service to London will retain broadly comparable or better services once HS2 is completed”</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> (Strategic C</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ase, 4.2.6).</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">On the other, it proposes that long distance services are diverted onto HS2, freeing capacity on the existing network for new services (</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Strateg</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ic C</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ase, Executive Summary, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> 57). </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> Figure 10 (</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Strategic Case </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">p.24) shows how, with HS2 taking </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">responsibility </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">most long-distance services, the number of commuter services into Euston can be increased greatly. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The same figure shows</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">though, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">that this comes through a </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">massive reduction in classic intercity </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">services</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">4. While it might be assumed that many passen</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">gers travelling between cities </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">such as Manchester, Birmingham and London </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">will be happy to use HS2 services instead of the classic intercity services that </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">HS2</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> will replace, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">HS2 cannot – by its nature – </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">exactly </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">replicate the current north-south intercity </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">timetables on the West Coast, East Coast and Midland Main Line</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">.  It will call at far fewer stations than current intercity services. If classi</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">c intercity services are reduce</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">d in number, the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">towns and cities </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">not served by HS2 trains, such as Stoke-on-Trent</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, Wilmslow and Stockport on the WCML, Leicester on the MML</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> and Wakefield and Doncaster on the ECML, will </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">almost certainly </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">face </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">reduction</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">direct services to London.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">5. Despite the Government’s claim that all towns and cities currently with direct serv</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ices to London should receive broadly comparable or better services, and that decisions on future services will be taken nearer the time, its own business case for HS2 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">is predicated on </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">significant </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">savings </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">being made through </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">reductions in </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">intercity services</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> on existing lines. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">These </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">classic line </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">savings’ </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">are a fundamental part of the business case, yet do not appear to be mentioned in the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Strategic Case document.  They may be found instead in </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The Economic Case for HS2 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">(October 2013) at</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><a href="http://assets.hs2.org.uk/sites/default/files/inserts/S%26A%201_Economic%20case_0.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://assets.hs2.org.uk/sites/default/files/inserts/S%26A%201_Economic%20case_0.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> (Table 9). This reveals that </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">savings of £8.2 billion are being </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">used to </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">offset </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">part of </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">the pr</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">edicted cost of operating HS2, thus reducing the ‘headline’ </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">operating cost</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">.  The </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">actual cost of operating the full HS2 network over the 60 year appraisal period is calculated to be £30,408 million.  Offset against this are savings from reductions in spendi</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ng on the existing </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">lins</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> of £8,265 million (savings on staff, electricity, diesel, lease costs, maintenance etc). This gives a headline figure </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">for the cost of operating HS2 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">of £22,143.  It is this latter figure that is used in the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">HS2 business case benefit-</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">cost ratio (</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">BCR</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">.  If all these classic savings were not to materialise, the BCR would </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">of course </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">significantly </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">lower.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">6. The reductions in classic line intercity services that </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">make up </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ose </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">£8.2 billion </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">of savings </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">may be found in </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">HS2 Ltd’s report </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">PFM </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">V.4.3 Assumptions report</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><a href="http://assets.hs2.org.uk/sites/default/files/inserts/S%26A%2020_PFM%20assumptions%20report.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://assets.hs2.org.uk/sites/default/files/inserts/S%26A%2020_PFM%20assumptions%20report.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">(section 6.4).  Comparing</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> the proposed classic line </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">intercity </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">service patterns with today’s intercity services revea</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ls that:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">West Coast intercity services between Manchester and London are predicted to be cut from 3 to 1 per hour (except at peak times in one direction only). This</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> would leave </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Stoke-on-</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Trent with half as many trains to London as today, Wilmslow with no direct services to London and Stockport's London service cut from 3 trains to 1 per hour. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:3pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Lancaster, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Oxenholme</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Penrith</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> and Carlisle are shown as having all their i</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ntercity services to London re-routed via Manchester, adding significantly to journey times.  It appears that the reason they will not receive any HS2 classic compatible services to London</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> in compensation, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">even though classic compatible services will run </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">on the WCML to Scotland, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">classic compatible trains </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">running from London to </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Scotland </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">will be </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">400</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">etre-long</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> sets which </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">divide </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">at </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Carstairs</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Junction (</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">one portion continuing to Glasgow and the other Edinburgh) </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">and it will not be possible for </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">hese long-formation trains </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">to fit onto the platforms </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">in Lanca</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ster  or </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Cumbria</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:3pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Liverpool's ordinary intercity services </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">to London would be </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">axed altogether, so it will be served by HS2 trains only.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> In peak times, this will leave </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">London-</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Liverpool </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">services </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ith fewer seats than today, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">because </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">the HS2 classic compatible train, at 200m, is shorter than the current </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">11-car </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Pendolino</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> A double-length HS2 service</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, at 400m,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> will not fit the platforms at Lime Street.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:3pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">On the East Coast Main Line, Wakefield and Doncas</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ter </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">see service cuts. Wakefield's service to London is halved</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> in the model</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">All direct services between London and Aberdeen and Inverness are axed</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> in the model</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">On the Midland Main Line, Leicester loses one of its 4 trains per hour to London,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> and Chesterfield loses one of its 2 trains per hour.  Sheffield and Nottingham city centre stations still see their services to London halved.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">7. In conclusion, the Government’s claim that no towns and cities will face worse services to London appears t</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">o be in conflict with its incorporation of £8.2 billion of classic line savings into the business case for HS2.  Without the</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> savings, the HS2 BCR will fall</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> significantly</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, but with them, it will be </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">extremely </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">difficult, we believe, to maintain </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">the level</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> of service </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">users of </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">current intercity services</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> to London</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> that the Government claims is their aim</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>